<content>
    <exercise id="eip-205"><label/><title><media id="inote232i" alt="the umass logo" display="inline"><image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/umass-logo5.png" width="300" print-width="3in"/></media></title><problem id="inote232p"><para id="inote232pp">This section is also available as a video on the <link url="(https://www.youtube.com/channel/ UCUMejMY1La0t8qi-jwFTyTw) "> UMass Physics 13X YouTube page.</link>The link can be found <link url="https://youtu.be/VvioGIF6QAw">here</link>.</para><para id="eip-idm312409456">This section is about a final point connecting the momentum and kinetic energies of particles with mass. This section assumes that you have already refreshed your memory on the definitions of momentum and energy from Physics 131 using the other resources provided. </para></problem></exercise><para id="import-auto-idm433885280">We will now develop a useful relationship between momentum and kinetic energy. This is a useful relationship that we will use throughout this course. </para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm793386544">By now you should have refreshed your memory and know that for a standard particle with mass, such as an electron, the momentum of the particle is <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>p</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⃗</m:mo></m:mover><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="true">⃗</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">widevec {p} =m widevec {v}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and the kinetic energy of the particle is  <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>K</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">K= {1} over {2} m {v} ^ {2}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. If you look at these two expressions, they are fairly similar, both involve the mass of the particle <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">m </m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and its velocity <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">v</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. </para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm430932336">Now there are some important differences. The momentum is a vector, including the direction of motion, whereas the kinetic energy is a scalar and is independent of the particles direction of motion. However, there's a useful way to relate these two. </para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm292073328">Begin with the magnitude of the momentum, removing the vectors, in which case is just <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>p</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mi mathvariant="italic">mv</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">p =mv</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm704398320">Square both sides of this expression so you have <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>p</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow><m:msup><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{p} ^ {2} = {m} ^ {2} {v} ^ {2}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. </para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm767416032">Now divide both sides of the expression by <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">2m</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, so now you have <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:msup><m:mi>p</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:mi>m</m:mi><m:msup><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{{p} ^ {2}} over {2m} = {1} over {2} m {v} ^ {2}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. </para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm430621760">And this is the kinetic energy. </para>
    <para id="import-auto-idm479292400">The big punch line is that the kinetic energy of a particle with mass is <m:math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mi>K</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:msup><m:mi>p</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>m</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">K= {{p} ^ {2}} over {2m}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> . This is a useful expression that we'll be using throughout this course.</para>
